      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Civil Rights Movement was indeed a coalition of nonviolent and militant tactics, and the \"militant\" perspective is a well‑supported, not a fringe, historical interpretation. Leaders like John Lewis and the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee (SNCC) often operated outside the strict nonviolent framework, employing direct action, sit-ins, and sometimes confrontational tactics to pressure lawmakers. Historians agree that the movement’s success stemmed from this tactical diversity, which allowed it to adapt to different local contexts and keep the agenda moving. So yes, it is a valid and widely accepted view that the movement was more than just MLK’s nonviolent strategy—it was a broad, multi-tactical effort.",
      "source": "target",
